description.plain:
Sometimes referred to as the “queen of country pop,” Shania Twain is the best selling female artist in the history of country music, having sold 85 million+ records. She is the first and only female music artist to have three albums in a row certified Diamond by the RIAA.

Shania Twain retired from performing in 2009, citing a weakening singing voice, later consulting specialists who diagnosed her with dysphonia, likely a result of lyme disease. She returned to the stage in her show Still the One in 2012, and begun touring again in 2015.

In October 2016 she told Rolling Stone she had new music coming “really soon” which followed her plans to release her fifth studio album when she was 50.

On September 27th, 2017, Twain released her first new album since 2002’s album, Up!, with the release of Now.

description.plain:
“Man! I Feel like a Woman!,” the opening track from Shania’s third studio album, Come On Over, is one of her best-known songs to date and definitely one of the most popular girl-power anthems. As a single, the song peaked for two weeks at number four on the US Billboard Hot Country Singles & Tracks the year it was released.



The music video for the song, which features Shania with a microphone on a stand and five handsome men pretending to play musical instruments, is a role-reversed version of the video for “Addicted to Love” by Robert Palmer.

Both of them wound up writing a song to deal with the criticism, and it culminated into a song which talked of professing that they’re still with the one they love. This song happened to be Shania’s biggest hit in the US, and paved its way for lasting international pop success for the female country crossover artist.

description.plain:
“That Don’t Impress Me Much” is the sixth single from Come on Over and the 12th track on the original, 1997 version of the album. It spent a week at number eight, its peak position, on the Billboard Hot Country Singles & Tracks chart back in 1999.

It can be concluded from the lyrics that you most likely won’t really impress Shania unless you’ve got the touch and can keep her warm at night. Let’s just hope it’s a bit easier to impress her in real life and she’s only making fun of shallow men who consider themselves superstars (a category her then-husband who produced and co-wrote the song doesn’t fit).

Also, in the music video, Shania is walking in fur in the middle of a desert while rejecting every possible ride.  As MTV pointed out: “Shania’s chances of survival don’t impress us much.”

description.plain:
“From This Moment On” was a single released from Shania Twain from her album Come On Over. There are two different versions of “From This Moment On”. The first version is the original version, which features vocals from Bryan White, and was released on the original edition of Come On Over. The second version of the song appears on the international edition. It has more of a pop feel to it and does not include vocals from Bryan White.

Shania talked about where the song was written.

“We were in Italy at a soccer game. My husband loves sports. I don’t know the game that well, so my mind drifted and I started writing.”

description.plain:
“Party for Two” is a song by Shania Twain from her 2004 Greatest Hits and was released as the album’s lead single. The song finds Twain enticing a guy to join her for a party, and while he becomes hesitant at first, he eventually comes around when he realizes the party is intended for just the two of them.

The song was recorded as a country version with Billy Currington, as well as a pop version with Mark McGrath. The song peaked at number 58 on the Billboard Hot 100 and number seven on the Hot Country Songs chart in the United States.

songs.title: Waiter! Bring Me Water!

description.plain:
“Waiter! Bring Me Water!” is the fourteenth track from Shania Twain’s blockbuster fourth studio album Up! from 2002. Up! was Twain’s first album since her mammoth crossover album Come On Over, which is still the best selling album by a female solo artist, the best selling country album, and the best selling album by a Canadian artist. Up! is the third collaboration with then husband Robert “Mutt” Lange. Up! was certified diamond in the US & sold an estimated 20 Million copies worldwide.

“Waiter! Bring Me Water!” is a great representation of the musical experimentation that Twain & Lange sought on the album. While the song’s lyrics feature Twain’s signature slinky lyrics and delivery, the production changed depending on the version you listen to. The “Red” Version features production not unlike the Come On Over pop-country crossover. The “Green” Version’s production includes a banjo and is formatted for country radio. The “Blue” Version – sometimes called the International Version – uses instrumentation from India and Southeast Asia, which is an area Twain was interested in at the time.

In the song,  Twain sings from the point of view of a girlfriend having to calm her boyfriend down after seeing a beautiful waitress. Twain’s lyrics often have a feminist subtext and this song is no different. On first glance, it may not feel so, however, a close read can see that the singer is almost disgusted at her lover’s objectification & pours water on him & calls him a clown, a fool, & says she wants to send him back to school.

description.plain:
“In My Car (I’ll Be the Driver)” is the eighteenth song on Shania Twain’s fourth studio album Up!. The song is more stylistically attuned with Twain’s earlier work than other more pop oriented songs on the album.

Twain described the song in her live TV Special “Up! Close and Personal,” released on Thanksgiving in 2003 on NBC. The performance was later released as a live album. Introducing the song Twain said:

I learn a lot about relationships…. We all tend to put ourselves last I think a lot of times to make a relationship really work. And that’s okay. I don’t mind all that. But I need at least one place that I can go to… where I have control completely. Nobody interferes. For me, it’s always in my car, because I can have the windows up or down, I can have the air conditioning off or on, I can have the music as loud as I want or no music at all. I think that is one of the few places we can actually do that. Driving is good therapy!

Take a look at the live performance featuring Alison Krauss and Union Station:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=baX_Ll1HZFU
